description:
Here is part 2 to the lesson posted on November 1st. Ted continues with the Gershwin classic “Our Love Is Here To Stay”, focusing on accompaniment. Video Credits: Cesar Pineda 03/19/97 

Here’s a brief summary for part two: 
1. Yes, even more walking chords. 
2. Seeing a pivotal or common finger between chords to make chord changes easier. 
3. Approaching a chord from its 5th.
4. Adding chord substitution to the progression.  

Trying to make sense of it all?  There is a lot here!  The best way to approach this lesson is to copy down his chords on a grid sheet and analyze why they are there over the given standard progression!  Remember Nat King Cole’s key is D flat!  You’ll have to transpose from whatever key your fake book key is in.  Again, there was not enough time to get through the entire song, but you now have the necessary tools to continue to the end.  I wish you good luck in your persistence to create beauty out of the mundane! 

Please visit https://tedgreene.com/ for blank chord grid sheets and for all things Ted.
